\section{Discussion and Conclusion}
\label{discussion}
Network operators are aiming to decrease the backhaul traffic as it will not be able to handle the requests coming from the users in the upcoming years. Therefore, caching at cell edges will have major effects in future cellular networks. In this paper we show that whether macro base stations use the optimal deployment strategy or store ``the most popular content", has very limited impact on the total hit probability.  It is, on the other hand, important to optimize the content placement strategy of the small cells and the total hit probability is increased significantly when the small cells use the optimal deployment strategy. It is shown that heuristic policies for small cells like storing the popular content that is not yet available in the macro base station results in significant performance penalties. To conclude, using the optimal deployment strategy for the small cells is crucial and it ensures the overall network to have the greatest possible total hit probability independent of the deployment policy of macro base stations.
